1️⃣ When to fork vs branch
Action	Use case
Fork	You want a completely separate copy of someone else’s repo on your GitHub account. Typically used for contributing to open-source or someone else’s private repo.
Branch	You’re working inside the same repo with your team. You stay connected to the main repo and can push changes directly (or via pull requests).

Since your project is already on GitHub and your team has access, you usually don’t need to fork — you can just create branches. Forks are mostly for:

External contributors

Open-source contributions

2️⃣ How to create a fork (on GitHub)

If you still want to fork:

Go to the repo on GitHub:
https://github.com/Inkbottle011/Boardgames.com

Click Fork (top-right corner)

GitHub creates a copy under your account

Clone your fork locally:

git clone git@github.com:YourUsername/Boardgames.com.git
cd Boardgames.com

Add the original repo as upstream to stay in sync:

git remote add upstream git@github.com:Inkbottle011/Boardgames.com.git

Pull changes from upstream when needed:

git fetch upstream
git merge upstream/main
3️⃣ When working with a team in Herd project

Since your teammates have access to the main repo, the simpler workflow is:

git checkout -b feature/your-feature  # create a branch

Work on your branch

Push to origin:

git push -u origin feature/your-feature

Make a pull request on GitHub → merge into main

This avoids creating unnecessary forks and keeps the history clean.

💡 Summary:

Team project → use branches, not forks

External contributor → fork, then PR

